DSL (Digital Subscriber Line): A popular broadband technology that utilizes existing telephone lines, allowing users to transmit both voice and data simultaneously at high speeds

Broadband Cable: Currently a common choice for internet access, it uses a cable modem connected via coaxial cable to provide high-speed service, often supplied by the same provider that offers cable television 

Satellite: An expensive option primarily used in locations where other services like phone lines, DSL, or cable are unavailable. While capable of decent download speeds, it is rarely used due to the availability of better alternatives

Mobile Hotspots: Portable devices or smartphone features that leverage cellular networks to provide wireless internet access to nearby devices 

ISDN (Integrated Services Digital Network): An older international standard for digital transmission over phone lines. Although faster than traditional dial-up, it was superseded by the higher speeds of DSL and cable 
